'''Upper Town''' ({{lang-el|ŒÜŒΩœâ Œ†œåŒªŒ∑}}, ''Ano Poli'') is the [[old town]] of [[Thessaloniki]], located around the city's [[acropolis]], north of the city center. [[File:Solun, stara fotografija.jpg|thumb|180px|Old photo]] [[File:Thessaloniki-Ano-Poli.png|thumb|180px|A street]] [[File:Thessalonikki, Macedonia, Greece779.jpg|thumb|180px|Street beside the walls]] he Upper Town is the most traditional part of the city, as it preserves much of the Byzantine and Ottoman era city fabric, otherwise destroyed in the [[Great Fire of Thessaloniki|great fire]] of 1917. Thus it features small stone-paved streets, old squares and houses in traditional Greek and [[Ottoman architecture]]. The Upper Town is the highest part of the city, and dominated by the acropolis, the Byzantine and Ottoman-era fort known as [[Heptapyrgion (Thessaloniki)|Heptapyrgion]]. The remaining [[Walls of Thessaloniki|city walls]] still ring the Upper Town, with many of its additional Ottoman and Byzantine structures still standing. The [[Church of Prophet Elijah (Thessaloniki)|church of Profitis Elias]], the [[Church of Saint Nicholas Orphanos]], the [[Byzantine Bath (Thessaloniki)|Byzantine bath]], the [[Church of Saint Catherine, Thessaloniki|Church of Saint Catherine]], such as the [[Atat√ºrk Museum (Thessaloniki)|Atat√ºrk Museum]] and the [[Alaca Imaret Mosque]] are also in the Upper Town. During the Ottoman period it was the main district of the Turks (Muslims) of the city, while the Greeks, western Europeans and the Jews were living around the [[Port of Thessaloniki|port]].
On clear days [[Mount Olympus]], at about 100&nbsp;km (62&nbsp;mi) away across the gulf, can also be seen towering the horizon.
